equences of not performing the activity. This method forces managers to justify all expenses and consider alternative ways of performing activities, ensuring an efficient allocation of resources. Decision packages are created for each activity a manager wishes to undertake, and they play a crucial role in the ZBB process [Data: Concepts (832); Relationships (693, 704)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"ZBB offers several benefits but also has notable drawbacks\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The benefits of ZBB include re-evaluating every activity, linking resource allocation to results and needs, developing a questioning attitude, encouraging a bottom-up approach to budgeting, and preventing budget creep. However, ZBB also has drawbacks such as the need for extensive training, unmanageable paperwork in large organizations, difficulty in ranking packages, time constraints for top-level management, and a potential focus on short-term goals over long-term objectives [Data: Concepts (833, 834); Relationships (709, 713)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"ZBB is particularly useful in the public sector\",\n            \"explanation\": \"ZBB is more prevalent in public sector bodies due to its transparency in showing budgets based on activities rather than line items. It is useful in ranking decision packages to allocate limited resources effectively. The public sector benefits from ZBB's ability to provide a clear justification for all expenses, making it easier to manage and prioritize spending [Data: Concepts (836); Relationships (718, 717)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"ZBB is most appropriate for organizations with high discretionary costs\",\n            \"explanation\": \"ZBB is most appropriate in organizations with a high portion of discretionary costs, such as research and development, training, and advertising. It enables reassessment of spending on discretionary items, ensuring that resources are allocated efficiently and effectively. This makes ZBB a valuable tool for organizations looking to optimize their budgeting process [Data: Concepts (835); Relationships (716, 707)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Case studies illustrate the practical application of ZBB\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The chapter includes case studies such as the transition of Plainfield County Public Authority Library from incremental budgeting to ZBB. This case highlights the evaluation of decision packages for computer upgrades, demonstrating the practical application and challenges of implementing ZBB. Another example is Newtown School, which faces recurring cash shortages and considers ZBB to manage discretionary spending more effectively [Data: Concepts (2167, 2170); Relationships (696, 694)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Features of ZBB promote a thorough and rational approach to budgeting\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The features of ZBB include focusing on activities or programs, asking critical questions about the necessity and cost of activities, and breaking the budgetary process into three stages: identifying activities, reviewing and ranking decision packages, and allocating resources. Unlike traditional budgets, ZBB emphasizes the activities or programs each department would like to undertake, ensuring a more efficient allocation of resources [Data: Concepts (831); Relationships (690, 699)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"ZBB's benefits and drawbacks must be balanced for effective implementation\",\n            \"explanation\": \"While ZBB offers several benefits such as re-evaluating activities and linking resource allocation to results, it also has drawbacks like the need for training and unmanageable paperwork. Effective implementation of ZBB requires balancing these benefits and drawbacks, ensuring that the organization can reap the advantages of ZBB while managing its challenges [Data: 