t and marketing strategies. Market Research serves as an external source of valuable information that helps businesses navigate the competitive landscape effectively.\n3. SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS, Sensitivity analysis calculates how responsive a decision is to changes in any of the variables used to calculate it.\nRelationships\n\nid,source,target,description\n10,FOCUS GROUP,MARKET RESEARCH,Focus group is related to market research. They are both research techniques to deal with uncertainty.\n11,MARKET RESEARCH,FOCUS GROUP,Market research is related to focus group. They are both research techniques to deal with uncertainty.\n\nOutput:\n{{\n    \"title\": \"Chapter 8: Risk and Uncertainty\",\n    \"summary\": \"Chapter 8 covers the following Learning Outcomes. C. Decision-Making Techniques 6. Dealing with risk and uncertainty in decision making a) Suggest research techniques to reduce uncertainty (e.g. focus groups, market research). b) Explain the use of simulation, expected values and sensitivity. c) Apply expected values and sensitivity to decision-making problems. d) Apply the techniques of maximax, maximin and minimax regret to decision-making problems, including the production of profit tables. e) Interpret a decision tree and use it to solve a multi-stage decision problem. f) Calculate the value of perfect and imperfect information. \",\n    \"rating\": 7.0,\n    \"rating_explanation\": \"The impact severity rating is high due to the fundamental importance of bookkeeping in accounting.\",\n    \"findings\": [\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Focus groups and market research are important research techniques to reduce uncertainty\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Companies often use focus groups and/or market research to deal with uncertainty. Focus groups are used to reduce uncertainty about new products by gathering opinions from a group of people in an interactive environment. Participants are chosen at random and may be observed by marketing professionals. Market Research involves the systematic gathering and analyzing of data about consumers, competitors, and market conditions to inform business decisions. It provides insights into market trends, customer preferences, and competitive dynamics. This process can be based on primary or secondary data and is used to assess the potential success of new product launches. By understanding consumers' needs and preferences, companies can make informed decisions about product development and marketing strategies. Market Research serves as an external source of valuable information that helps businesses navigate the competitive landscape effectively. [Data: Concepts (1, 2); Relationships (10, 11)]\"\n        }},\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Explain and apply sensitivity analysis to decision-making problems\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Sensitivity analysis calculates how responsive a decision is to changes in any of the variables used in making that decision. It looks at one variable at a time and measures how much the variable can change by (in percentage terms) before affecting the decision. The smaller the percentage, the more sensitive the decision is to that variable. Sensitivity % = Profit/Variable  [Data: Concepts (3)]\"\n        }}\n    ]\n}}\n\n# Real Data\n\nUse the following text for your answer. Do not make anything up in your answer.\n\nText:\n-----Entities-----\nhuman_readable_id,title,description,degree\n830,\"\"\"ZERO-BASED BUDGETING (ZBB)\"\"\",\"Zero-Based Budgeting (ZBB) is a budgeting method where all expenses must be justified for each new period, starting from a 'zero base.' This approach requires the costs and benefits of all activities to be quantified and justified, making it particularly useful in the public sector, although it is costly and time-consuming to implement. ZBB involves developing the budget from an assumption of no existing resources, necessitating that all resources be justified and compared with alternatives.\n\nThe process of ZBB includes three main steps: identifying activities and creating decision packages, ranking these packages by their benefits, and allocating resources based on priority. Managers are required to identify activities, consider different ways of performing them, and describe them in a 'decision package' that analyzes costs, states purposes, and identifies alternative methods. This method forces managers to justify all expenses and consider alternative ways of performing activities, ensuring an efficient allocation of resources. Every function within an organization is analyzed for its needs and costs, promoting a thorough and rational approach to budgeting.\",9\n832,\"\"\"DECISION PACKAGE\"\"\",\"A decision package in zero-based budgeting (ZBB) is a comprehensive document that serves multiple purposes. It analyzes the cost of an activity, states its purpose, identifies alternative methods of achieving the same purpose, establishes performance measures, and assesses the consequences of not performing the activity or performing it at different levels. Essentially, a decision package is a mini-budget prepared for each activity a manager wishes to undertake. This includes a base level package and incremental packages, which help in analyzing the cost and benefits of each activity.\",7\n837,\"\"\"ZBB\"\"\",\"Zero-Based Budgeting (ZBB) is a budgeting method where all expenses must be justified for each new period, starting from a 'zero base.' Every function within an organization is analyzed for its needs and costs.\",8\n831,\"\"\"FEATURES OF ZBB\"\"\",\"\"\"FEATURES OF ZBB\"\" include focusing on activities or programs, asking critical questions about the necessity and cost of activities, and breaking the budgetary process into three stages: identifying activities, reviewing and ranking decision packages, and allocating resources. Unlike traditional budgets, which are typically produced using a 'line item' approach that lists each type of expense and the amount budgeted by each department, ZBB emphasizes the activities or programs each department would like to undertake. It considers questions such as the necessity and efficiency of each activity.\",6\n833,\"\"\"BENEFITS OF ZBB\"\"\",\"\"\"Benefits of ZBB include re-evaluating every activity, linking resource allocation to results and needs, developing a questioning attitude, encouraging a bottom-up approach to budgeting, and preventing budget creep.\"\"\",6\n834,\"\"\"DRAWBACKS OF ZBB\"\"\",\"\"\"Drawbacks of ZBB include the need for training, the unmanageable amount of paperwork in large organizations, difficulty in ranking packages, time constraints for top-level management, complexity and time consumption, inability to react to changes during the year, and potential prioritization of short-term goals over long-term objectives.\"\"\",6\n836,\"\"\"USE OF ZBB IN THE PUBLIC SECTOR\"\"\",\"\"\"ZBB is more prevalent in public sector bodies due to its transparency in showing budgets based on activities rather than line items, and its usefulness in ranking decision packages to allocate limited resources effectively.\"\"\",6\n835,\"\"\"WHEN ZBB IS APPROPRIATE\"\"\",\"\"\"ZBB is most appropriate in organizations with a high portion of discretionary costs, such as research and development, training, and advertising. It enables reassessment of spending on discretionary items.\"\"\",6\n2167,\"\"\"EVALUATING DECISION PACKAGES AND ZBB TRANSITION FOR PLAINFIELD COUNTY PUBLIC AUTHORITY LIBRARY\"\"\",\"\"\"Plainfield County Public Authority (PCPA) has transitioned from incremental budgeting to zero-based budgeting (ZBB). The library manager is considering two decision packages for computer upgrades to respond to criticism of the library being old-fashioned. The decision packages include costs for staff, IS maintenance, and website hosting, with varying impacts on library operations and costs.\"\"\",3\n2168,\"\"\"DECISION PACKAGE 1: COMPUTER UPGRADE\"\"\",\"\"\"This decision package involves replacing only the computers at a total cost of $45,000. Annual IS maintenance costs will fall to $9,000, while annual website costs and staff costs will remain constant. This upgrade will not substantially change library operations.\"\"\",2\n2169,\"\"\"DECISION PACKAGE 2: COMPUTER UPGRADE AND INTEGRATED LIBRARY SYSTEM\"\"\",\"\"\"This decision package involves purchasing new computers plus additional hardware and software to automate core library processes at a total cost of $98,500. It will allow self-service borrowing of books, reduce staff members to four, increase annual IS maintenance costs to $22,000, and increase annual website costs to $3,000.\"\"\",2\n1771,\"\"\"PERFORMANCE MANAGEMENT AND BUDGETING APPROACHES FOR YUMI CO'S RESTAURANTS\"\"\",\"\"\"Yumi Co owns several rural restaurants with a loyal customer base and low profit margins. The company uses annual budgets prepared by head office, split into monthly targets. A new competitor in Cowly has raised concerns about achieving profit targets. The monthly performance statement for the Cowly restaurant shows variances in revenue and costs, highlighting the need for effective cost monitoring and performance management.\"\"\",1\n1770,\"\"\"USE OF ZBB AT NEWTOWN SCHOOL\"\"\",\"\"\"Newtown School faces recurring unexpected cash shortages due to incremental budgeting. Zero-based budgeting (ZBB) could help by establishing decision packages for discretionary activities, such as different levels of lunch service and sports education, to prioritize spending more effectively. However, ZBB is time-consuming and may not be suitable for all categories of expenditure.\"\"\",1\n2171,\"\"\"ADVANTAGES OF ZBB\"\"\",\"\"\"Advantages of ZBB include a focus on the objectives and needs of the community, evaluation of decision packages by value for money, involvement of the library manager in the budgeting process, and identification of operational efficiencies and quality improvements.\"\"\",1\n2170,\"\"\"DECISION PACKAGE 2\"\"\",\"\"\"Decision package 2 involves a computer upgrade including an integrated library system costing $98,500, annual IS maintenance costs of $22,000, website hosting costs of $3,000, and staff costs of $112,000, totaling $235,500 for the first year.\"\"\",1\n2172,\"\"\"DISADVANTAGES OF ZBB\"\"\",\"\"\"Disadvantages of ZBB include being time-consuming for the library manager, potential distraction from other important responsibilities, and a focus on short-term objectives over long-term benefits.\"\"\",1\n\n\n-----Relationships-----\nhuman_readable_id,source,target,description,rank\n693,\"\"\"ZERO-BASED BUDGETING (ZBB)\"\"\",\"\"\"DECISION PACKAGE\"\"\",\"\"\"Zero-based budgeting (ZBB) involves the creation of decision packages to analyze and justify activities and their costs.\"\"\",16\n691,\"\"\"ZERO-BASED BUDGETING (ZBB)\"\"\",\"\"\"BUDGETARY CONTROL SYSTEM\"\"\",\"\"\"Zero-based budgeting (ZBB) is a method used within a budgetary control system that starts 'from scratch' and requires all costs and benefits to be justified.\"\"\",16\n704,\"\"\"DECISION PACKAGE\"\"\",\"\"\"ZBB\"\"\",\"\"\"ZBB involves the creation of decision packages for each activity a manager wishes to undertake.\"\"\",15\n690,\"\"\"ZERO-BASED BUDGETING (ZBB)\"\"\",\"\"\"FEATURES OF ZBB\"\"\",\"\"\"Features of ZBB describes the key characteristics and approach of Zero-Based Budgeting.\"\"\",15\n709,\"\"\"BENEFITS OF ZBB\"\"\",\"\"\"ZBB\"\"\",\"\"\"ZBB offers several benefits including re-evaluating activities, linking resource allocation to results, and preventing budget creep.\"\"\",14\n713,\"\"\"DRAWBACKS OF ZBB\"\"\",\"\"\"ZBB\"\"\",\"\"\"ZBB has several drawbacks such as the need for training, unmanageable paperwork, and difficulty in ranking packages.\"\"\",14\n718,\"\"\"USE OF ZBB IN THE PUBLIC SECTOR\"\"\",\"\"\"ZBB\"\"\",\"\"\"ZBB is more prevalent in public sector bodies due to its transparency and usefulness in ranking decision packages.\"\"\",14\n716,\"\"\"WHEN ZBB IS APPROPRI